{"title_page": "Niels Arestrup", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name          = Niels Arestrup\n|image         = Niels Arestrup C\u00e9sars 2014.jpg\n|caption       = Arestrup at the [[2014 C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1949|2|8|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n|occupation    = Actor, film director, screenwriter\n|years_active  = 1973&ndash;present\n|children      = 2\n}}\n\n'''Niels Arestrup''' ({{IPA-fr|nils a\u0281est\u0281yp}}; born 8 February 1949) is a French actor, film director and screenwriter. He won three [[C\u00e9sar Awards]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Paris]] into a family of modest means; his father was [[Danish people|Danish]] and his mother was [[Bretons|Breton]].\n\nArestrup has won three [[C\u00e9sar Awards]] for [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for ''[[The Beat That My Heart Skipped]]'' and ''[[A Prophet]]'', then ''[[Quai d'Orsay (film)|Quai d'Orsay]]''. The two first films were directed by [[Jacques Audiard]]. He is the most awarded in this category.\n\n==Theater==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Author\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1973\n| ''La Famille''\n| Lodewijk De Boer\n| [[Derek Goldby]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Crime and Punishment]]''\n| [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky]]\n| [[Andr\u00e9 Barsacq]]\n|\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Deathwatch (play)|Deathwatch]]''\n| [[Jean Genet]]\n| Claude Mathieu\n|\n|-\n| 1976-77\n| ''[[Gilles de Rais]]''\n| [[Roger Planchon]]\n| [[Roger Planchon]]\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Platonov (play)|Platonov]]''\n| [[Anton Chekhov]]\n| Gabriel Garran\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[The Cherry Orchard]]''\n| [[Anton Chekhov]]\n| [[Peter Brook]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1982\n| ''La Derni\u00e8re Nuit de l'\u00e9t\u00e9''\n| [[Aleksei Arbuzov]]\n| Yves Bureau\n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Lover (play)|The Lover]]''\n| [[Harold Pinter]]\n| Philippe Ferran\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1983\n| ''[[The Cherry Orchard]]''\n| [[Anton Chekhov]]\n| [[Peter Brook]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Miss Julie]]''\n| [[August Strindberg]]\n| [[Andreas Voutsinas]]\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Dom Juan]]''\n| [[Moli\u00e8re]]\n| [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]] \n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Fool for Love (play)|Fool for Love]]''\n| [[Sam Shepard]]\n| [[Andreas Voutsinas]]\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''B29''\n| Alain Page\n| [[Derek Goldby]]\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''2050, le radeau de la mort''\n| Harald M\u00fcller\n| Hans-Peter Cloos\n|\n|-\n| 1988\n| ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]''\n| [[Anton Tchekhov]]\n| [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]]\n|\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[The Seagull]]''\n| [[Anton Tchekhov]]\n| [[Andrei Konchalovsky]] \n|\n|-\n| rowspan=3|1990\n| ''Tout contre un petit bois''\n| [[Jean-Michel Ribes]]\n| [[Jean-Michel Ribes]]\n|\n|-\n| ''Sade, concert d'enfers''\n| Enzo Cormann\n| [[Philippe Adrien]] \n|\n|-\n| ''[[The Misanthrope]]''\n| [[Moli\u00e8re]]\n| Pierre Pradinas\n|\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''Ecrit sur l'Eau''\n| [[\u00c9ric-Emmanuel Schmitt]]\n| Niels Arestrup\n|\n|-\n| 1993\n| ''[[Letters to a Young Poet]]''\n| [[Rainer Maria Rilke]]\n| Niels Arestrup\n|\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[La Musica deuxi\u00e8me]]''\n| [[Marguerite Duras]]\n| Bernard Murat\n|\n|-\n| 1996\n| ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]''\n| [[Edward Albee]]\n| [[John Berry (film director)|John Berry]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1999\n| ''\u00c9toiles''\n| Pierre Laville\n| [[Maurice B\u00e9nichou]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Copenhagen (play)|Copenhagen]]''\n| [[Michael Frayn]]\n| [[Michael Blakemore]]\n| Prix du Syndicat de la critique - Best Actor<br />Nominated - [[Moli\u00e8re Award for Best Actor]]\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Fernando Krapp m\u2019a \u00e9crit cette lettre''\n| [[Tankred Dorst]]\n| Bernard Murat\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2002\n| ''[[Ph\u00e8dre]]''\n| [[Jean Racine]]\n| [[Jacques Weber]] \n|\n|-\n| ''Une nuit arabe''\n| [[Roland Schimmelpfennig]]\n| Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric B\u00e9lier-Garcia\n| \n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Each In His Own Way]]''\n| [[Luigi Pirandello]]\n| Bernard Murat\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2004\n| ''L'Homme, la b\u00eate et la vertu''\n| [[Luigi 