rance|Denmark}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arestrup, Niels}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French male film actors]]\n[[Category:French male television actors]]\n[[Category:French people of Breton descent]]\n[[Category:French people of Danish descent]]\n[[Category:Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:French film directors]]\n[[Category:French male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:French screenwriters]]\n[[Category:20th-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century French male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Paris]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor C\u00e9sar Award winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP IMDb refimprove|only=yes|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Niels Arestrup\n|image         = Niels Arestrup C\u00e9sars 2014.jpg\n|caption       = Arestrup at the [[2014 C\u00e9sar Awards]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1949|2|8|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n|occupation    = Actor, film director, screenwriter\n|years_active  = 1973&ndash;present\n|children      = 2\n}}\n\n'''Niels Arestrup''' ({{IPA-fr|nils a\u0281est\u0281yp}}; born 8 February 1949) is a French actor, film director and screenwriter. He won three [[C\u00e9sar Awards]].\n\n==Biography==\nHe was born in [[Paris]] into a family of modest means; his father was [[Danish people|Danish]] and his mother was [[Bretons|Breton]].\n\nArestrup has won three [[C\u00e9sar Awards]] for [[C\u00e9sar Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] for ''[[The Beat That My Heart Skipped]]'' and ''[[A Prophet]]'', then ''[[Quai d'Orsay (film)|Quai d'Orsay]]''. The two first films were directed by [[Jacques Audiard]]. He is the most awarded in this category.\n\n==Theater==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Author\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1973\n| ''La Famille''\n| Lodewijk De Boer\n| [[Derek Goldby]]\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Crime and Punishment]]''\n| [[Fyodor Dostoyevsky]]\n| [[Andr\u00e9 Barsacq]]\